'''Timothy Eric Boswell''', known as '''Tim Boswell''', (born [[December 2]], [[1942]]) is a [[United Kingdom|British]] [[politician]], and is the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] [[Member of Parliament]] (MP) for [[Daventry (UK Parliament constituency)|Daventry]].

The son of a [[farmer]], Tim Boswell was educated at [[Marlborough College]] and [[New College, Oxford]], where he obtained a degree in [[Classics]] and a diploma in [[agriculture|agricultural]] [[economics]]. He joined the [[Conservative Research Department]] in [[1966]], becoming head of the economics section in [[1974]]. He stood for [[British House of Commons|Parliament]] at the [[United Kingdom general election, 1974 (February)|February 1974 General Election]] in [[Rugby, Warwickshire|Rugby]] but was defeated by [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour's]] William Price by 6,154 votes.

Tim Boswell has had a 480 [[Acre#UK definition|acre]] farm in [[Northamptonshire]] since 1974, he was elected as the Treasurer of the Daventry Conservative Association in [[1976]] and subsequently its Chairman from [[1979]]-[[1983]]. He became a political advisor to the [[Minister of Agriculture, Fisheries and Food]] [[Michael Jopling, Baron Jopling|Michael Jopling]] for two years from [[1984]].

Boswell was chosen to contest the Daventry constituency after the sitting Conservative MP and former [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]] [[Cabinet]] member [[Reg Prentice]] had announced his retirement. Tim Boswell was elected as the Conservative MP for Daventry at the [[United Kingdom general election, 1987|1987 General Election]] with a majority of 19,690 and has held the seat very comfortably since.

Tim Boswell's [[Palace of Westminster|Westminster]] career began unsurprisingly as a Member of the [[Ministry of Agriculture, Fisheries and Food|Agriculture]] [[Select Committee]] in [[1987]]. He became the [[Parliamentary Private Secretary]] to the [[Secretary to the Treasury#Financial Secretaries to the Treasury, 1852-present|Financial Secretary to the Treasury]] [[Peter Lilley]] in [[1989]]. Tim Boswell entered [[John Major|John Major's]] government in [[1990]] as an [[Whip (politics)|Assistant Government Whip]], following the [[United Kingdom general election, 1992|1992 General Election]] he was promoted within the Whip's Office and became a Lord Commissioner to the Treasury.

In December 1992, Tim Boswell was appointed [[Parliamentary Under Secretary of State]] at the [[Department of Education]] and moved in the same position at the [[Ministry of Agriculture, Fisheries and Food]] until the Major government fell at the [[United Kingdom general election, 1997|1997 General Election]].

In opposition Boswell was a spokesman on the [[HM Treasury|Treasury]] in the immediate aftermath of the [[1997]] election defeat and became a spokesman on [[Department of Trade and Industry|Trade and Industry]] under [[William Hague]], before speaking on [[Department of Education and Skills|Education and Employment]] in [[1999]] until after the [[United Kingdom general election, 2001|2001 General Election]]. He became the spokesman for [[Department of Work and Pensions|Work and Pensions]] under the leadership of [[Iain Duncan Smith]], moving briefly to speak on [[Department of Constitutional Affairs|Constitutional Affairs]] in [[2003]] under [[Michael Howard]] and back to Work and Pensions in [[2004]], where he remains following the [[United Kingdom general election, 2005|2005 General Election]].

Tim Boswell is married to Helen Delahy Rees and they have three daughters. Within his constituency he can boast [[Silverstone]], the home of the [[British Grand Prix]]; [[Althorp]], the childhood home of [[Diana, Princess of Wales]] and her brother the [[Charles Spencer, 9th Earl Spencer|Earl Spencer]]; and Thenford, the village of the mansion home of [[Michael Heseltine]].

On 31 March 2006, he announced his intention not to contest the next general election, provided it does not take place unexpectedly soon.  The Daventry seat is due to be split in two before the [[Next United Kingdom general election|next general election]], with the northern part becoming part of a new Daventry constituency and the southern part becoming part of a [[South Northamptonshire (UK Parliament constituency)|South Northamptonshire]] constituency.

